processData({"ClubName":"Brighton","ClubWebsiteURL":"http://www.seagulls.co.uk","NewsItem":[{"ArticleURL":"http://www.seagulls.co.uk/news/article/oscar-luck-is-an-attitude-996066.aspx","NewsArticleID":"tcm:229-996066-16","PublishDate":"2013-08-16 01:15:04 PM","ThumbnailImageURL":"http://ec2-54-247-103-134.eu-west-1.compute.amazonaws.com:8095/Images/oscar-ff229-955710_240X320_tcm229-996066-16.jpg","Title":"Oscar: Luck is an Attitude","textContent":" Oscar Garcia is convinced his players have the correct attitude to put an end to Albion’s winless start to the campaign.

The Seagulls go in search of their first victory of the season at St Andrew's on Saturday, and Oscar believes his squad are in the right frame of mind to change their fortunes on the pitch.

He told seagulls.co.uk, “Luck is an attitude and we are working hard, and I hope as soon as possible, we will get what we deserve.

“It’s only the start and in all of the games we were close to winning, or getting a better result. All the players want to play and work hard to change this.

“The small details in the last three games haven’t gone in our favour but we will try and change this as we were close to winning those games.

“It’s not easy to play Birmingham away, but we don’t care if play home or away. We will try to attack and get the three points.

“We have a strong team and strong players, experienced players. I’m sure we will get what we deserve soon.”

Oscar’s squad have been hit with a spate of injuries recently but the Spaniard says that will not alter his approach for the trip to the midlands.

 “We have had some problems with injuries, we have many players who cannot play but the players we have will go to Birmingham to try and get the win.

“We are expecting a difficult game away at St Andrews. It will not be easy, but all the games in the Championship are very difficult – but we will go with the same mentality. To keep the ball, to attack and to get the three points.”

The 32-year-old defender, who skippered Albion to the League One title in 2011, recently received international recognition; being named in Gordon Strachan’s last two Scotland squads.

Albion head coach Oscar Garcia admitted holding onto Greer was one of his priorities when he arrived at the club in the summer.

Garcia told seagulls.co.uk, “One of my targets when I arrived here was to keep Gordon here because he is the captain and he’s a leader. For me, he is very important this season.”

Greer has made over 100 appearances for Albion since joining from Swindon in 2010, finding the net twice.

The Albion midfielder has been selected by coach Chris Coleman, following a solid start to the season, and is hoping to build on his 24 international caps.

He told seagulls.co.uk, "It is nice to get call up and I am looking forward to meet up with the boys. I got called up a couple of times last year but missed out through a hamstring injury, so it is nice to be back in the mix.

"After last season’s injury I feel good, really fit and really hungry.

"It is only a short trip as the game is on Wednesday but it is against Ireland, a Home Nations match, so it should be a good match."

","base64JpegImg":""},{"ArticleURL":"http://www.seagulls.co.uk/news/article/ulloas-mixed-emotions-985378.aspx","NewsArticleID":"tcm:229-985378-16","PublishDate":"2013-08-11 12:27:51 PM","ThumbnailImageURL":"http://ec2-54-247-103-134.eu-west-1.compute.amazonaws.com:8095/Images/ulloa-f229-985349_240X320_tcm229-985378-16.jpg","Title":"Ulloa’s Mixed Emotions","textContent":" Despite grabbing his second goal in as many league games, Leonardo Ulloa admitted the results are disappointing him.

The striker had put Albion 1-0 up against Derby, only for Chris Martin’s brace to condemn the Seagulls to a third straight defeat.

He told seagulls.co.uk, “From one point of view I’m happy to be scoring goals but I want the goals to be part of a win, which is the most important thing. It drives you mad to go ahead and end up losing.

"We have to keep working and turn things around and we need to learn how to control a game when we are 1-0 up, that is important.

“We thank the fans for supporting us but we want to give them a bit more. I think everybody can still do a bit more and we have to do that – especially now.

“Bit by bit we are getting there but there are things that are not going for us.”

The Argentine also highlighted missing players as a cause for some of Albion’s misfortune, with Liam Bridcutt and Andrea Orlandi the latest absentees.
 
“We have had injuries, and also players who are arriving, so all that is not helping. But when the team gets into its rhythm I think we will be fine.

“The only thing that is missing is results to go with the goals."

Off the pitch, Ulloa has also revealed his family have now moved to England, which should help him on it.

"It was hard last season not having my family here but now I know they are here, I know they are waiting when I get home and that helps.

“Having them here makes me more calm and happy.”
","base64JpegImg":""},{"ArticleURL":"http://www.seagulls.co.uk/news/article/andrews-experiences-influenced-move-984221.aspx","NewsArticleID":"tcm:229-984221-16","PublishDate":"2013-08-10 06:57:48 PM","ThumbnailImageURL":"http://ec2-54-247-103-134.eu-west-1.compute.amazonaws.com:8095/Images/andrews-f229-983864_240X320_tcm229-984221-16.jpg","Title":"Andrews: Experiences Influenced Move","textContent":" Keith Andrews has revealed his past experiences when playing Albion had played a part in his decision to join the club.

The latest addition to Oscar Garcia’s squad - on a season-long loan from Bolton - made his debut as a second-half sub against Derby to complete a whirlwind week.

The midfielder told seagulls.co.uk, "Brighton have always been an absolute nightmare to play against - it’s the way they dominate possession so, as the opposition, this isn’t a place you look forward to coming too. You know you’re always in for a tough afternoon.

“I played a game for Bolton on Tuesday and trained Thursday as normal. Then I had a few calls Thursday afternoon and it all happened very quickly and I arrived here yesterday at noon.

“I want to play at the highest level that I can and that’s why I’m here. I’m joining a squad that has a wealth of experience that will make me become the player I know I can be. The style of football that they play here was also something that really appealed to me."

As for the role he may be asked to fulfil in Garcia’s side, the Republic of Ireland international admits he is happy to play wherever he is asked.

“I’m quite adaptable. I still feel I can get forward and chip in with a few goals by playing a little bit more advanced but, equally, if the manager wants me to sit in front of the back four then that’s something I’m very happy to do to.

“I feel like I can have a big impact here. I’ve got a very good feeling about the place and the people have made me feel very welcome. I’m sure the results will come.”
","base64JpegImg":""},{"ArticleURL":"http://www.seagulls.co.uk/news/article/oscar-we-will-improve-984082.aspx","NewsArticleID":"tcm:229-984082-16","PublishDate":"2013-08-10 06:57:11 PM","ThumbnailImageURL":"http://ec2-54-247-103-134.eu-west-1.compute.amazonaws.com:8095/Images/oscar-ff229-983870_240X320_tcm229-984082-16.jpg","Title":"Oscar: We Will Improve","textContent":" Oscar Garcia tonight told Albion fans to rest assured that his side will improve, despite a third defeat of the season against Derby County at the Amex today.

The Seagulls head coach told seagulls.co.uk, "This is not the start I would have dreamed of, if I had it would not have been these three results, but it is a long season and we will improve.

"We are disappointed and sad for the fans. I want to say thank you to the fans for the support they gave us again.

"Today was like the other games. We had lots of chances to score, but again we were not clinical in front of goal. They had three chances and scored two goals.

"We are performing well, but need to be much sharper in both penalty areas, when we are attacking and defending.

"I’m more disappointed at not converting the chances we had than with the goals we conceded. I would be worried if we were not creating chances, we are just not clinical enough.

"I want us to think about what is happening and why. Again we started well but then after scoring we dropped a little and in this competition you have to play 100% for the entire game.

"You cannot afford to not be less than 100% for even one or two minutes, as in this league the opposition will capitalise and punish you.

"After the second goal from Derby we played more in the way I want us to play, but it should not take the other team scoring to change our mentality. We will make a few small changes and for sure we will improve."

Oscar refused to blame Andy D'Urso's decision not to award a penalty shortly before half-time, when Paul Coutts appeared to raise his arm and block David Lopez's free kick with his hand with the score at 1-1.

Despite his reluctance to point the finger at the officials, the Spaniard has already been on the end of three controversial refereeing decisions since he arrived in England.

He added, "I hope soon it will be different and we will have a bit of luck in our favour. Against Leeds they scored after a handball; against Newport the referee sent off Calde; today he did not consider it a penalty.

"We are waiting for the luck to come our way. It was a clear handball, but these things happen, we have to deal with them and I am waiting for the day that this can change and work in our favour."

Oscar will also hope his luck changes this week in terms of injuries and that he has Andrea Orlandi fit for next Saturday's trip to Birmingham, but it is unlikely Liam Bridcutt or Bruno will be back.

Keith Andrews will be in contention for a full debut after coming off the bench today.

"I do not know how long Liam is out for with his groin injury. He will not be joining up with Scotland. I hope that Andrea will be okay for next weekend. We cannot be 100% as we will have to check his progress every day.

"We are pleased to have Keith Andrews here. He is a leader, he is an experienced player, he is comfortable with the ball and he wanted to come from the first minute he knew that we wanted him.

"I think he can help us a lot, but we still need some more signings. Like any coach I want us to have as many good players as possible."
